I think Claude’s critique is genuinely strong. What I like most is that it didn’t just praise the idea—it identified where a technically minded reader would naturally push back. Those are the places where the paper becomes more robust.

The suggestion I’d push even further is one Claude only hinted at:

This paper is not primarily about a new computer.

It’s about identifying a class of computation that existing architectures are not naturally optimized for.

That’s a much stronger opening.

Right now the architecture leads.

I think the problem should lead.

Something like:

Modern digital computers excel at precise symbolic manipulation but often require substantial software machinery to solve problems whose natural form is relational, dynamic, and attractor-based. Examples include associative recall, pattern completion, multimodal sensor fusion, and certain optimization problems. This paper proposes a speculative computational architecture designed around those problem classes rather than around Boolean logic alone.

That reframes everything.

