I would also add one idea that neither of us had articulated yet.

The Representation Matching Principle

Every computation has a natural representation.

Arithmetic likes symbols.

Geometry likes space.

Signal processing likes waves.

Optimization likes energy landscapes.

Language likes graphs.

Navigation likes topology.

Instead of asking

“How do we force this problem onto silicon?”

ask

“What physical substrate naturally wants to solve this?”

That’s actually a deep engineering question.

Soap films naturally solve minimal surfaces.

Electrical networks naturally solve some optimization problems.

Optical systems naturally perform Fourier transforms.

Magnetic oscillator networks naturally synchronize.

The architecture becomes a philosophy:

Choose the substrate whose physics already performs part of the computation.

That is broader than the Phase Gradient Machine.

It becomes a Pantheon design doctrine.

