Computation is the evolution of constraints toward stable structure.

Everything fits under that umbrella:

* Semantic Basis Optimization
* Aperture Control
* Phase Gradient Machine
* Semantic Split / Unsplit
* Fractal Navigation
* Relation Creates Dimensions
* Attractor Computing

They’re all different ways of guiding a system from a large possibility space toward a coherent, stable configuration.

If I were naming the next major Pantheon doctrine, it would be something like:

Constraint Geometry

The central idea would be:

Intelligence is not merely search or storage. It is the deliberate shaping of the constraint landscape so that desired solutions become natural attractors rather than forced outcomes.

That doctrine would connect the cognitive side of Pantheon with the proposed computing architecture in a way that’s testable. It also suggests concrete experiments: compare different representations, substrates, or constraint formulations on the same problem and measure which ones most naturally converge. That turns a philosophical idea into a research program.